* Evasion in Nmap is the technique of modifying scan behavior to bypass firewalls, IDS/IPS, and security filters while scanning a target.

#--data-length 50
•	•  Nmap appends 50 bytes of random data to each probe packet.
•	•  Packet payload size becomes non-standard.
•	•  The packet is less recognizable to basic IDS/firewall signatures that expect standard packet sizes.

Example :
•	Instead of a standard TCP SYN with no data, it becomes:
o	TCP SYN + 50 bytes of random payload.

#-f 
•	It fragments IP packets into smaller pieces (typically 8-byte fragments)
•  For example, one TCP SYN packet (used in scanning) might be ~60 bytes.
•  With -f, Nmap splits that 60-byte packet into multiple 8-byte fragments.

NOTE: What Happens Without -f , Nmap sends a full TCP SYN packet.

#-g <portno>
•	It changes the source port number (the port Nmap uses on your machine to send packets).

For Example : Many firewalls allow incoming traffic from port 53 (DNS), so spoofing your scan to appear as DNS traffic may help you bypass firewall rules.


